{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LNDoKhALasmGWujAu3sn9r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"Now I have a clear picture. This is a TOP-level decompose task (Complexity: —). I need to:\n\n1. Identify the top-level components of the platform (networked monolith)\n2. Determine which are atomic vs composite\n3. Write documentation files\n4. Emit the `<response>` XML block\n\nLet me think through the component breakdown:\n\n**Platform Structure:**\n- Single binary: `cmd/platform/main.go`\n- Two HTTP listeners: metrics (8081) and IAM (8082)\n\n**Top-level components:**\n\n1. **metrics** (composite or atomic?) — The metrics service handles POST /events and GET /events. \n\nIt needs a store and handlers, which is straightforward enough that I'll classify it as atomic. The in-memory event storage and the two HTTP endpoints are simple enough to treat as a single cohesive unit.\n\n2. **iam** (composite) — IAM is \"internally composed of two logical components: (\n\na) user authentication and lifecycle, and (b) authorisation/RBAC.\" This is explicitly composite, so I'll break it into sub-components: lifecycle handles user auth and management endpoints, authz-rbac handles role and permission checking, and then I'll need an integrate-iam component to wire them together.\n\n3. **integrate-platform** (atomic) — The top-level integration step that brings metrics and IAM into the platform binary.\n\nFor metrics, the in-memory event storage with POST and GET handlers is small enough to stay atomic.\n\nSo my top-level structure is: metrics (atomic), iam (composite), and integrate-platform (atomic), with both metrics and iam living under `internal/`.\n\nSince `internal` is a Go convention directory, I skip the composite-level documentation and let each child component write its own README when decomposed.\n\nNow I need to figure out the description fields carefully. iam into the platform's main entry point, wiring both the metrics listener on 8081 and IAM listener on 8082, then writing end-to-end acceptance tests that exercise all 12 endpoints across both services. Since `internal/` is a Go convention directory, I'll skip the README and theory-of-operation docs — those will be written by each composite child if they're decomposed later. Now I need to flesh out the full API descriptions for each component, starting with the complete contract for metrics including all endpoint details from the acceptance spec. Now I need to wire both the metrics and IAM services into a single platform binary, starting the metrics listener on port 8081 and the IAM listener on port 8082 in separate goroutines. The acceptance tests should cover all 12 endpoints across both services—the metrics endpoints for event creation and retrieval, plus the IAM endpoints for user management, authentication, and authorization operations. I'm checking the exception rule for Go convention directories — since `internal/` is a standard Go pattern, I should skip writing docs for it and let each child component document itself later. The metrics service is small and atomic with just two endpoints, while the IAM service is clearly composite with ten endpoints spanning user lifecycle, auth, and RBAC concerns. I need to make sure I'm using the correct package path as the source directory for metrics.\n\nNow I'm ready to compose the response — I'll skip the parent directory docs since it's a Go convention, write a detailed contract for metrics with all endpoint specifics, keep the IAM description brief since it's composite, and provide full wiring and acceptance criteria for the integrate-platform component.","signature":""}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1025,"cache_read_input_tokens":20394,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1025},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"171908ab-5e21-4bbe-9d27-3f46ca50bfe5","uuid":"f2372902-4571-484d-85fc-0a197463ed57"}
{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01LNDoKhALasmGWujAu3sn9r","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"Now I have everything I need. Let me think through the decomposition.\n\n## Decomposition Analysis\n\n**Platform structure:** single binary `cmd/platform/main.go`, two independent HTTP listeners (metrics on 8081, IAM on 8082). The context explicitly flags IAM as having two internal sub-components (lifecycle + authz-rbac).\n\n**Top-level components:**\n\n**1. `metrics` — atomic**\nPath: `internal/metrics`. Two endpoints (POST /events, GET /events), one in-memory store, HTTP handlers. Small enough to implement in a single pass.\n\n**2. `iam` — composite**\nPath: `internal/iam`. Ten endpoints across three logical groups (user lifecycle, authentication, RBAC). The prompt explicitly says IAM is \"internally composed of two logical components.\" This needs further decomposition into lifecycle and authz-rbac sub-components before it can be implemented.\n\n**3. `integrate-platform` — atomic**\nThe TOP-level integrate step. Writes `cmd/platform/main.go`, wires both listeners, and runs end-to-end acceptance tests covering all 12 endpoints from the spec.\n\n**Common parent path:** `internal/` — this is a Go language-convention directory (`internal`), so the documentation exception applies. I skip writing `README.md` and `theory-of-operation.md` at the composite level; each child will produce its own documentation when decomposed.\n\n**Description verbosity check:**\n- `metrics` is atomic + HTTP-handling → full API contract required, copied verbatim from acceptance-spec.md\n- `iam` is composite → one-line description sufficient\n- `integrate-platform` is the TOP integrate step → full wiring + all 12 endpoints from acceptance-spec.md required\n\n<response>\n  <outcome>ARCHITECT_DECOMPOSITION_READY</outcome>\n  <handoff>The platform decomposes into three top-level components: (1) metrics — an atomic in-memory event-recording service serving two endpoints on port 8081; (2) iam — a composite identity-and-access-management service serving ten endpoints on port 8082, itself requiring further decomposition into lifecycle and authz-rbac sub-components; and (3) integrate-platform — the TOP-level atomic wiring step that produces cmd/platform/main.go, starts both listeners in goroutines, and runs end-to-end acceptance tests against all 12 endpoints. The common parent directory is internal/, a Go convention directory, so no composite-level README or theory-of-operation is written at this pass — each child produces its own documentation when decomposed.</handoff>\n  <components>\n    <component>\n      <name>metrics</name>\n      <complexity>atomic</complexity>\n      <source_dir>internal/metrics</source_dir>\n      <description>In-memory metrics service for recording and listing frontend user interaction events. Serves on port 8081.\n\nHTTP API (verbatim from spec):\nPOST /events — body: {\"type\":\"click-mouse\"|\"submit-form\",\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"payload\":{}} → 201 with event object {\"id\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"type\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"payload\":{}};\nGET /events → 200 JSON array of event objects, each with fields: id, type, userId, payload.\n\nData model: Event{id string, type string, userId string, payload map[string]interface{}}.\nStore: thread-safe in-memory slice; IDs are generated UUIDs on POST.\nPackage layout: store.go (EventStore with Add/List), handlers.go (PostEvent, GetEvents), routes.go (returns http.Handler).\nUnit tests must cover store and handler logic; handler tests use net/http/httptest.</description>\n    </component>\n    <component>\n      <name>iam</name>\n      <complexity>composite</complexity>\n      <source_dir>internal/iam</source_dir>\n      <description>Identity and access management listener (port 8082) composed of two sub-components — lifecycle (user CRUD and authentication) and authz-rbac (roles and permission checks) — that together handle all ten IAM HTTP endpoints.</description>\n    </component>\n    <component>\n      <name>integrate-platform</name>\n      <complexity>atomic</complexity>\n      <source_dir>.</source_dir>\n      <description>Wire the metrics and iam components into a single binary at cmd/platform/main.go. The binary starts the metrics HTTP listener on port 8081 and the IAM HTTP listener on port 8082 in separate goroutines, then blocks until a shutdown signal. There must be exactly one main package in the entire codebase.\n\nEnd-to-end acceptance tests (net/http against live listeners started in TestMain or a helper) must cover all 12 endpoints verbatim from the spec:\n\nMetrics listener (port 8081):\nPOST /events body:{\"type\":\"click-mouse\",\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"payload\":{}} → 201 {\"id\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"type\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"payload\":{}};\nPOST /events body:{\"type\":\"submit-form\",\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"payload\":{}} → 201 (same shape);\nGET /events → 200 JSON array containing previously posted events.\n\nIAM listener (port 8082):\nPOST /users body:{\"username\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"password\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} → 201 {\"id\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"username\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} (no password field);\nGET /users/{id} → 200 {\"id\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"username\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} or 404;\nDELETE /users/{id} → 200/204 on existing user or 404 on missing;\nPOST /auth/login body:{\"username\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"password\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} → 200 {\"token\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"};\nPOST /auth/logout header:Authorization:Bearer &lt;token&gt; → 200/204;\nPOST /roles body:{\"name\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"permissions\":[\"&lt;string&gt;\"]} → 201 {\"id\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"name\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"permissions\":[\"&lt;string&gt;\"]};\nGET /roles → 200 JSON array;\nPOST /users/{id}/roles body:{\"roleId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} → 200/201;\nGET /users/{id}/roles → 200 JSON array;\nPOST /authz/check body:{\"userId\":\"&lt;string&gt;\",\"permission\":\"&lt;string&gt;\"} → 200 {\"allowed\":&lt;bool&gt;}.</description>\n    </component>\n  </components>\n</response>"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"stop_details":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":1025,"cache_read_input_tokens":20394,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":1025},"output_tokens":20,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"171908ab-5e21-4bbe-9d27-3f46ca50bfe5","uuid":"25008df1-61e9-4584-9331-33408c8f8339"}
